##Jiang Li: Each doctor accumulates the so-called experience, is a patient to teach

Micro Signal, Peopleweekly

Feature description, portrait of the Times.

The anoxic patient is like a person walking up a cliff, the road is always flat, walking forward when he can not see the cliff, doctors can not see. Next thing you know, one of his feet is gone

This pneumonia really upends years of experience with ordinary pneumonia... the so-called experience that every doctor has accumulated in the face of a brand-new disease is taught to us by one patient after another who has died

This article first appeared in the southern people's weekly
By Yang Nan and Zhang Mingmeng, staff writers

The medical staff pressed against the glass to show their colleagues outside the records of the patients

The interview was delayed until 10:30 p.m. due to some unforeseen circumstances. I asked Jiang Li if she wanted to change it to the next day, and she said tonight, Tomorrow Is Dragon head, there will be volunteers to give the doctor a haircut. It's also the first time she's had her hair cut on a "February 2" day, so make the most of it.

On February 24, the second day of the second lunar month, Jiang Li arrived in Wuhan for a full month. She is the director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Xuanwu Hospital, Capital Medical University, and one of the first experts dispatched by the National Health Commission to Support Wuhan.

Jiang Li's chat with a huge amount of information, she has clinical experts at the same time the detailed experience and national experts of macro-thinking. For the past month of critical care, she frankly informed her Golden Pool Hospital Critical Care Ward of the difficulties, pointed out that our current understanding of new pneumonia still has many limitations. Each patient has helped humanity to understand the progression of the disease, and sometimes that progression comes at a terrible cost.

The key to cure the new coronary patients lies in the "advance of the pass" . One of the contents of Jiang Li's work is to visit the general wards of three other hospitals, to identify and screen out key patients among ordinary patients, and to intervene and treat them as soon as possible. The work is sometimes more grueling than being in a gold and silver lake intensive care unit because of the size of the stock, but Jiang said it was something she was especially willing to do because it was a key proposition in reducing mortality.

Photos of ward visits in other hospitals provided by Jiang Li / interviewees

I can finally see the cliffs

Southern People Weekly: You to Wuhan a month, the understanding of the condition of what kind of change?

Jiangli: It's been four weeks now, and it's slowly becoming clear what kind of path the survivors are on. The first patients were all very sick, and they left before they knew what was going on, and the same thing happens every day. We thought we couldn't do this all the time, start with the workflow, manage the patients more carefully. The staff of the Golden Pool come from all parts of the country, and each has its own division of Labor. It is very difficult to get to know all the patients. A very urgent patient, immediately to the rescue, to intubate, and even too late to understand what he is, has been sick for how long.

There is also a very inconvenient place, which is the structure of the ward of an Infectious Disease Hospital, where the patient, the suction machine and the blood gas machine, the venous pump are inside (contaminated area) . Drugs, laboratory reports, medical records, imaging films are outside (non-contaminated area) . Normally, when we work, we have access to the files at any time, anywhere, in and out, not here. Inside I had to think about what I had just seen on the computer outside. On the outside, I want to know what I'm doing on the inside. Then I took a piece of paper, outside to record some basic information about the patient, and a piece of paper to write down what I was doing inside. However, what you bring in can not be brought out, so you put it on the glass for your colleagues to take photos and pass them to the work group.

In the beginning, there was a big debate about when to intubate, whether to intubate or not? What exactly is that critical node. An easy way to determine the extent of respiratory failure clinically is to see if he can complete a sentence. I have a patient who can always. He can drink, he can look at his cell phone, and he needs a nutrient solution every day, just to get better and go home. You can see in him that he wants to live. He is a strong middle-aged man, about 50 years old. The people in their 50s and 60s were the hardest hit this time.

The first patients to be intubated will have carbon dioxide retention, Hypercapnia, and his body won't be able to expel the carbon dioxide. This usually occurs in the very advanced stages of pneumonia. But this time it happened earlier. Carbon Dioxide retention, usually regulated by breathing, improves somewhat, but this time is very difficult. Found that the virus will also attack the heart muscle, which is not common pneumonia.

It's not that the heart stops working in the first place, but that at some point, when the heart starts working, it stops. You could put it this way: All the cells are injured, and it's just grinding its teeth and doing its job, until it reaches a tipping point.

But the patient did not exhibit typical heart failure, and the circulation collapsed completely. This is not the same as a normal heart failure, which is clinically typical, so maybe a diuretic will do the trick. Heart dysfunction and myocardial cell damage can not be completely equated, new coronary pneumonia in the early does not show heart failure. It's that every cell in the patient is injured, but it's still working, so the heart is doing fine, and then suddenly at some point, every cell stops working.

Medics and family members transfer a patient in Wuhan on Feb. 24

Photograph by Chen Zhuo

Southern People Weekly: In intensive care to touch some of the rules?

Jiang Li: I have a patient who was hospitalized on January 18th and fell ill a week before he was admitted. He is still using a breathing machine and has had a tracheotomy. It's not looking good. You know, I had a little bit of a fight about whether or not I wanted to stick with it. First wave of patients came here, and almost every one of them was rushed in, and by the time it was his turn, his heart had stopped. We didn't have the manpower. It happened all the time. We gave him an emergency intubation, but his brain is already damaged from lack of oxygen, and if he recovers, he'll probably be a vegetable. We usually perform a tracheotomy in about two weeks for people who are hooked up to a machine, but he may not wake up. Thus the risks of tracheotomy (a high-risk procedure) and the benefits to the patient become less clear. He's in a coma. He's got a tube in his mouth. He's got some dirt. I did a tracheotomy to make him more or less comfortable. Well, in the eyes of the doctors, this patient does not mean that he can live after this treatment, and the ethical and moral considerations will be a little more.

With what I know now, I could have intubated sooner. When he was just having a bad lung, I tried to fix it. When something else goes wrong, like a kidney failure, like a circulation problem, it can be very hard to hold on to. It gets harder and harder. It's not 1 + 12.

At first we looked at the course of the disease, and those who were suffering from hypoxia were like a person walking up a cliff, the road was always flat, and he could not see the cliff as he went along, nor could the doctor. Next thing you know, one of his feet is gone. Now we're finally learning to see how far away the cliff is, knowing we're going to fall. But only understand its occurrence, development, has not been able to learn to quickly block the progress of a link. As doctors, all we can do for now is monitor him as he goes, and when he's about to fall, lift him up, see if he can hold, and maybe some people will.

Southern People Weekly: If you know you're going to fall, why did you trust him?

DJANGO: sometimes you don't know what's going to happen. Other Times, people who are already halfway there, like in this case, if the patient doesn't make it, I want him to leave with dignity. That's what a doctor does.

If the doctor says the person must not be good, such as the patient's previous quality of life is not good, or he is very old, there are many accompanied by disease, this patient I also advocate not too actively intubation. Two GRANDMAS, almost 80 years old, came in with white lungs on both sides. For one, the lungs are in such bad shape that the pain of further treatment may far outweigh the benefits. When she got worse, the nurse asked me twice, and I told her that you could let her go without end-of-life resuscitation. Grandma soon went into a coma, and I gave her a little blood pressure medication to keep the patient's circulation going until the end. The second grandma, I intubated her myself. When I went in to check on her, I didn't think she was okay, and I had to get something ready to intubate, because I didn't have time. I was there for more than an hour after intubation, breathing heavily, and the patient was slightly stable. But then I came out of the room and I looked at one more film, and I realized it was probably for nothing because it was so bad.

From my own point of view, it's kind of like war. The principle of battlefield care is to give priority to soldiers who can quickly regain their fighting strength. When medical resources are limited, the proper use of resources should be carefully evaluated.

Southern People Weekly: Critical death rate, is there a change now?

Jiang Li: The mortality rate is certainly different for patients with different disease severity. According to my ward, the mortality rate is high. Finally, put your numbers together, you might get a more objective answer. I think the real case-fatality rate is probably now no one can be accurately calculated, neither the numerator nor the denominator is completely accurate.

On February 13, medical staff were busy in the ICU of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital

I was especially willing to walk around all the general wards every day and pick out patients who were about to have problems

Southern People Weekly: How can we better treat critically ill patients?

Jiang Li: This is a whole project. First we must find a way to input the patients into the hospital. After the initial problem is solved, it is possible to move the "pass forward" . The rescue of critical patients also needs to move the "pass forward" , to make it less of a nightmare for the general ward. Things have been looking up lately. If the front floor can be advanced, and our floor can be advanced in time, the patient will have a chance as long as he holds up.

The other day they asked me what I wanted to do, and I said the thing I wanted most was for you to let me go into the shelter and I would screen, or for you to let me go into the General Ward and I would screen people for you, and I would just use my eyes and my experience to transfer as many of the most severe cases as possible, he needs better care. One of the things I particularly like to do is go around all the general wards every day and pick out patients who look like they're going to be sick and have a chance to get into the ICU and be cared for.

There was a patient that day, and I told them if I didn't deal with him, he'd probably be gone in the next hour, and I could tell. Was He unconscious? He smokes fast, doesn't he? Does he put a lot of effort into it? Is his heart rate fast, too? BP's dropping. Pulse ox is dropping. These were all signs that he had reached the edge of the cliff, and that it would only take a moment to let go.

Today, I went through the list of patrol inspections one by one and put together a list of maybe 20 or so people. I say we go to the other wing, take a quick look, and there won't be that many people in each wing.

Isn't there a distinction between critical and critical care in the guidelines? But in fact, for clinical practice, is dynamic, maybe the patient is critical one hour, critical the next hour, I went to see today, there are several critical patients, have improved back to critical.

The treatment of critically ill patients, with his hospital medical equipment, such as whether there is breathing machine, oxygen pressure enough, but also with the staff, like us, twice the number of medical staff is not enough. There is also a very big impact factor, is the courage and responsibility of health care workers, in the face of infection risk this thing, people and the difference is not small.

Southern People Weekly: how important is the subjective part in ICU rescue?

Jiang Li: Now there are two problems, one is staffing is really not enough, I double the nurses, let each nurse is responsible for 1 / 2 of the work now, the quality will be better. Another paramedic has yet to overcome her fear. Every ICU patient survives on a shift by shift basis. If one class doesn't do a good job, it reverses the work of many classes in front of it.

Southern People Weekly: Now the difference between the level of treatment in different hospitals big?

Jiang Li: no small. Usually in Beijing, each hospital's ICU, in the same hospital's different ICU all has the very big difference. And now there are a number of non-medical factors in the interaction, such as a ward by three medical teams put together, we do not necessarily think the same way. Objectively, everyone's treatment habits, ordinary work habits are different, as well as the understanding of this new disease has a process.

Worksheet of Jiang Li in ICU on 6th floor of Kam Yin Tam South provided by interviewees

The cost for doctors to understand how the disease develops is enormous

Southern People Weekly: Some doctors pointed out that some patients may have lung CT images have been all white, he is serious, even critical illness, but he can walk, eat and talk to you, it seems that everything is normal, why there is such a phenomenon?

DJANGO: Yeah, it's weird. Aren't we called Acute respiratory distress syndrome? But some patients aren't embarrassed. Normally, when the oxygen levels are that low, you'd think you'd be gasping for air, but now the patient's wandering around on his cell phone. I guess it's because the body's feedback mechanism is broken, which is really hard to understand. The pneumonia really upended years of experience watching ordinary pneumonia.

I remember a previous study, on Everest, where the partial pressure of oxygen was extremely low, about 26. Because the oxygen in the air is low, that the human body to the low oxygen compensation tolerance ability is very strong. If this guy's just hypoxic, he's not GonNa die right away.

Normally during Hypoxia, there's some sort of reflex that the receptor senses, and the patient compensates by panting. Perhaps the body's compensation mechanism was disrupted by the virus this time.

Southern People Weekly: There are also cases that have been transferred out of the severe illness, but patients feel uncomfortable, asked to re-CT, found that the lung disease has worsened.

Jiang Li: People feel uncomfortable, is a very complex, by multiple factors to form a common feeling, hypoxia is only one aspect. Generally speaking, I prefer to trust the patient's feelings, and vice versa. When I judge whether a person is better, I ask him, "How do you feel? " If he feels stronger, speaks in a loud voice, his face lights up, and his eyes move, he just got better.

Southern People Weekly: What impressed patients have you saved so far?

DJANGO: actually, I remember everyone. Doctors recognize that the disease develops at the cost of one life after another.

Southern People Weekly: Are you facing death at a higher density this month than before?

DJANGO: Not Really, but there are a lot of unexpected deaths. Death doesn't go according to plan. There are some patients who can't hold on. He's gone. We've done everything we can for him. He's gone. There are patients who can hold it, and you know exactly what the patient is supposed to do at each stage of the disease, and you do all of these things, hold it as long as you can, hold it as long as you can, and he might have a chance, but he's gone. But either way, buy the patient some time, maybe he'll get better.

We want to reduce the number of accidental deaths, and in most cases, doctors can predict. But there are some patients, that the doctor doesn't see on the day they leave, or they don't know until the next day that they're gone, and we need to find a way to reduce that.

Southern People Weekly: Is this going to have an impact on you?

Jiang Li: it would be a great pity. Our daily job is to be reluctant or reluctant to allow this to happen. Doctors don't do anything wrong subjectively, but they do have a lack of awareness, and that's the price. Facing A brand-new disease, every doctor accumulates the so-called experience, is a patient who died taught us.

Medical workers treat a critically ill patient Chen Zhuo in the severe isolation ward of the Red Cross Hospital in Wuhan on Feb. 17

NUCLEIC ACIDS can be false negative at diagnosis. Why can't they be false negative when they go out?

Southern People Weekly: Now face the disease, because there are many unknown parts, cognitive difficulty, this difficulty will make you feel depressed?

DJANGO: It doesn't depress me. The way I work is changing. But there is also a problem that there is no single top department that can deploy all the people in all the departments, so there is no movement of people between the provinces, between the medical teams. In fact, the core purpose of ICU is to concentrate a group of doctors, a group of nurses, a group of equipment, doctors and nurses to use this equipment, they have professional knowledge, and then focus on the treatment of the next batch of serious patients. Of course, now slowly improving, these two days we are doing a tour, the purpose is to get these potential seriously ill patients out, put a better hospital. In fact, the need is to comb out a good workflow, but this is very difficult, in the gold and silver pool we have a ward comb for a long time.

Southern People Weekly: Do you think the ICU is equipped with enough equipment?

Jiang Li: compared with the lack of more than under. Many hospitals do not have breathing machines, or very little. So they might not be able to stop the patient from getting worse. How many new pneumonia patients are in the hospital right now. All of these patients have a common need for oxygen.

Southern People Weekly: Now there are a number of cases, cured and discharged from the hospital and then tested positive for nucleic acid, you think more likely why?

DJANGO: We don't know enough about this virus. According to autopsy, it's been around longer than we thought, so I always thought we should find a place for him to stay for two weeks after he gets out, but I also know that this will cause a great social burden. You think all these people had circled around for a while before coming to the hospital sick. They finally got out. The whole process took about a month at the hospital. The first week, they went into hiding, the symptoms are evident by week 2, and if they are better by week 3, they will not be able to walk quickly. So normally the whole thing takes about three to four weeks, and then you get out of here, you give him two more weeks, and then you have to find a place to put it... and since you're diagnosing it, the nucleic acid could be false negative, why can't you go out with a false negative?

Southern People Weekly: You tend to think he wasn't completely cured when he left the hospital.

Jiang Li: Pneumonia imaging is relatively slow to fully absorb, and most people's shadows will remain. In general, what kind of cases do we talk about when pneumonia discharge? No fever, hypoxemia corrected, no dyspnea, the patient feels fine, and is usually discharged. But didn't we figure out the pattern this time? I think we should find some of these (false negative) cases that meet current discharge criteria and see if they still have the poison on them. There's so much here to study seriously.
